# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graph-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The **Bellman–Ford algorithm** is an algorithm that computes shortest paths from a single source vertex to all of the other vertices in a weighted digraph.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] It is slower than Dijkstra's algorithm for the same problem, but more versatile, as it is capable of handling graphs in which some of the edge weights are negative numbers.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Alfonso Shimbel (1955), but is instead named after Richard Bellman and Lester Ford Jr., who published it in 1958 and 1956, respectively.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Moore also published a variation of the algorithm in 1959, and for this reason it is also sometimes called the **Bellman–Ford–Moore algorithm**.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Negative edge weights are found in various applications of graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a graph contains a "negative cycle" (i.e. a cycle whose edges sum to a negative value) that is reachable from the source, then there is no *cheapest* path: any path that has a point on the negative cycle can be made cheaper by one more walk around the negative cycle.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In such a case, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can detect and report the negative cycle.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Like Dijkstra's algorithm, Bellman–Ford proceeds by relaxation, in which approximations to the correct distance are replaced by better ones until they eventually reach the solution.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In both algorithms, the approximate distance to each vertex is always an overestimate of the true distance, and is replaced by the minimum of its old value and the length of a newly found path.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In each of these repetitions, the number of vertices with correctly calculated distances grows, from which it follows that eventually all vertices will have their correct distances.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] This method allows the Bellman–Ford algorithm to be applied to a wider class of inputs than Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The intermediate answers and the choices among equally short paths depend on the order of edges relaxed, but the final distances remain the same.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Bellman–Ford runs in $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ time, where $|V|$ and $|E|$ are the number of vertices and edges respectively.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Simply put, the algorithm initializes the distance to the source to 0 and all other nodes to infinity.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then for all edges, if the distance to the destination can be shortened by taking the edge, the distance is updated to the new lower value.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The core of the algorithm is a loop that scans across all edges at every loop.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Since the longest possible path without a cycle can be $|V|-1$ edges, the edges must be scanned $|V|-1$ times to ensure the shortest path has been found for all nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] A final scan of all the edges is performed and if any distance is updated, then a path of length $|V|$ edges has been found which can only occur if at least one negative cycle exists in the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The edge (u, v) that is found in step 3 must be reachable from a negative cycle, but it isn't necessarily part of the cycle itself, which is why it's necessary to follow the path of predecessors backwards until a cycle is detected.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The above pseudo-code uses a Boolean array (`visited`) to find a vertex on the cycle, but any cycle finding algorithm can be used to find a vertex on the cycle.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] A common improvement when implementing the algorithm is to return early when an iteration of step 2 fails to relax any edges, which implies all shortest paths have been found, and therefore there are no negative cycles.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In that case, the complexity of the algorithm is reduced from $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ to $O(l\cdot |E|)$ where l is the maximum length of a shortest path in the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the inductive case, we first prove the first part.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Consider a moment when a vertex's distance is updated by `v.distance := u.distance + uv.weight`.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` is the length of some path from *source* to *u*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then `u.distance + uv.weight` is the length of the path from *source* to *v* that follows the path from *source* to *u* and then goes to *v*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the second part, consider a shortest path *P* (there may be more than one) from *source* to *v* with at most *i* edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Let *u* be the last vertex before *v* on this path.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` after *i*−1 iterations is at most the length of this path from *source* to *u*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, `uv.weight + u.distance` is at most the length of *P*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In the *ith* iteration, `v.distance` gets compared with `uv.weight + u.distance`, and is set equal to it if `uv.weight + u.distance` is smaller.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, after *i* iterations, `v.distance` is at most the length of *P*, i.e., the length of the shortest path from *source* to *v* that uses at most *i* edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] If there are no negative-weight cycles, then every shortest path visits each vertex at most once, so at step 3 no further improvements can be made.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Conversely, suppose no improvement can be made.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] I.e., every cycle has nonnegative weight.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] When the algorithm is used to find shortest paths, the existence of negative cycles is a problem, preventing the algorithm from finding a correct answer.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] However, since it terminates upon finding a negative cycle, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used for applications in which this is the target to be sought – for example in cycle-cancelling techniques in network flow analysis.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] A distributed variant of the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used in distance-vector routing protocols, for example the Routing Information Protocol (RIP).
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm is distributed because it involves a number of nodes (routers) within an Autonomous system (AS), a collection of IP networks typically owned by an ISP.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each node sends its table to all neighboring nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] When a node receives distance tables from its neighbors, it calculates the shortest routes to all other nodes and updates its own table to reflect any changes.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] With this early termination condition, the main loop may in some cases use many fewer than |*V*| − 1 iterations, even though the worst case of the algorithm remains unchanged.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The following improvements all maintain the $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ worst-case time complexity.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] A variation of the Bellman–Ford algorithm described by Moore (1959), reduces the number of relaxation steps that need to be performed within each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a vertex *v* has a distance value that has not changed since the last time the edges out of *v* were relaxed, then there is no need to relax the edges out of *v* a second time.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In this way, as the number of vertices with correct distance values grows, the number whose outgoing edges that need to be relaxed in each iteration shrinks, leading to a constant-factor savings in time for dense graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] This variation can be implemented by keeping a collection of vertices whose outgoing edges need to be relaxed, removing a vertex from this collection when its edges are relaxed, and adding to the collection any vertex whose distance value is changed by a relaxation step.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] In China, this algorithm was popularized by Fanding Duan, who rediscovered it in 1994, as the "shortest path faster algorithm".
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Yen (1970) described another improvement to the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] His improvement first assigns some arbitrary linear order on all vertices and then partitions the set of all edges into two subsets.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] The first subset, *Ef*, contains all edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* < *j*; the second, *Eb*, contains edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* > *j*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is visited in the order *v1*, *v2*, ..., *v*|*V*|, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Ef*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is then visited in the order *v*|*V*|, *v*|*V*|−1, ..., *v*1, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Eb*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each iteration of the main loop of the algorithm, after the first one, adds at least two edges to the set of edges whose relaxed distances match the correct shortest path distances: one from *Ef* and one from *Eb*.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] This modification reduces the worst-case number of iterations of the main loop of the algorithm from |*V*| − 1 to $|V|/2$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Another improvement, by Bannister & Eppstein (2012), replaces the arbitrary linear order of the vertices used in Yen's second improvement by a random permutation.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] This change makes the worst case for Yen's improvement (in which the edges of a shortest path strictly alternate between the two subsets *Ef* and *Eb*) very unlikely to happen.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] With a randomly permuted vertex ordering, the expected number of iterations needed in the main loop is at most $|V|/3$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Fineman (2024), at Georgetown University, created an improved algorithm that with high probability runs in ${\tilde {O}}(|V|^{8/9}\cdot |E|)$ time.
[src:graph-algorithms/bellman-ford-algorithm] Here, the ${\tilde {O}}$ is a variant of big O notation that hides logarithmic factors.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] For example, in a chess endgame, a chess engine may build the game tree from the current position by applying all possible moves and use breadth-first search to find a winning position for White.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Implicit trees (such as game trees or other problem-solving trees) may be of infinite size; breadth-first search is guaranteed to find a solution node if one exists.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] In contrast, (plain) depth-first search (DFS), which explores the node branch as far as possible before backtracking and expanding other nodes, may get lost in an infinite branch and never make it to the solution node.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Iterative deepening depth-first search avoids the latter drawback at the price of exploring the tree's top parts over and over again.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] On the other hand, both depth-first algorithms typically require far less extra memory than breadth-first search.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search can be generalized to both undirected graphs and directed graphs with a given start node (sometimes referred to as a 'search key').
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] In state space search in artificial intelligence, repeated searches of vertices are often allowed, while in theoretical analysis of algorithms based on breadth-first search, precautions are typically taken to prevent repetitions.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] BFS and its application in finding connected components of graphs were invented in 1945 by Konrad Zuse, in his (rejected) Ph.D. thesis on the Plankalkül programming language, but this was not published until 1972.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Moore, who used it to find the shortest path out of a maze, and later developed by C.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Lee into a wire routing algorithm (published in 1961).
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] The below pseudocode finds the shortest path from a given root vertex to all other vertices in the graph using BFS.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] 2. it checks whether a vertex has been explored before enqueueing the vertex rather than delaying this check until the vertex is dequeued from the queue.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of this breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterative depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a breadth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] The queue Q contains the frontier along which the algorithm is currently searching.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Nodes can be labelled as explored by storing them in a set, or by an attribute on each node, depending on the implementation.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] The *parent* attribute of each node is useful for accessing the nodes in a shortest path, for example by backtracking from the destination node up to the starting node, once the BFS has been run, and the predecessors nodes have been set.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search produces a *breadth-first tree*.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] The diagrams on the right show the breadth-first tree obtained by running a BFS on an example graph of German cities (upper diagram) starting from *Frankfurt*.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] The time complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|+|E|)$ , as every vertex and every edge will be explored in the worst case. $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ is the number of edges in the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Note that $O(|E|)$ may vary between $O(1)$ and $O(|V|^{2})$ , depending on how sparse the input graph is.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] When the number of vertices in the graph is known ahead of time, and additional data structures are used to determine which vertices have already been added to the queue, the space complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] This is in addition to the space required for the graph itself, which may vary depending on the graph representation used by an implementation of the algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] In the analysis of algorithms, the input to breadth-first search is assumed to be a finite graph, represented as an adjacency list, adjacency matrix, or similar representation.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] However, in the application of graph traversal methods in artificial intelligence the input may be an implicit representation of an infinite graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] In this context, a search method is described as being complete if it is guaranteed to find a goal state if one exists.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search is complete, but depth-first search is not.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] When applied to infinite graphs represented implicitly, breadth-first search will eventually find the goal state, but depth first search may get lost in parts of the graph that have no goal state and never return.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] An enumeration of the vertices of a graph is said to be a BFS ordering if it is a possible output of the application of BFS to this graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a graph with n vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Recall that $N(v)$ is the set of neighbors of v .
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Let $\sigma =(v_{1},\dots ,v_{m})$ be a list of distinct elements of V , for $v\in V\setminus \{v_{1},\dots ,v_{m}\}$ , let $\nu _{\sigma }(v)$ be the least i such that $v_{i}$ is a neighbor of v , if such a i exists, and be $\infty$ otherwise.
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Let $\sigma =(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be an enumeration of the vertices of V .
[src:graph-algorithms/breadth-first-search] Equivalently, $\sigma$ is a BFS ordering if, for all $1\leq i<j<k\leq n$ with $v_{i}\in N(v_{k})\setminus N(v_{j})$ , there exists a neighbor $v_{m}$ of $v_{j}$ such that $m<i$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] A version of depth-first search was investigated in the 19th century by French mathematician Charles Pierre Trémaux as a strategy for solving mazes.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The time and space analysis of DFS differs according to its application area.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] In theoretical computer science, DFS is typically used to traverse an entire graph, and takes time $O(|V|+|E|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ the number of edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] This is linear in the size of the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] In these applications it also uses space $O(|V|)$ in the worst case to store the stack of vertices on the current search path as well as the set of already-visited vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Thus, in this setting, the time and space bounds are the same as for breadth-first search and the choice of which of these two algorithms to use depends less on their complexity and more on the different properties of the vertex orderings the two algorithms produce.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] For applications of DFS in relation to specific domains, such as searching for solutions in artificial intelligence or web-crawling, the graph to be traversed is often either too large to visit in its entirety or infinite (DFS may suffer from non-termination).
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] In such cases, search is only performed to a limited depth; due to limited resources, such as memory or disk space, one typically does not use data structures to keep track of the set of all previously visited vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] For such applications, DFS also lends itself much better to heuristic methods for choosing a likely-looking branch.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] When an appropriate depth limit is not known a priori, iterative deepening depth-first search applies DFS repeatedly with a sequence of increasing limits.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] In the artificial intelligence mode of analysis, with a branching factor greater than one, iterative deepening increases the running time by only a constant factor over the case in which the correct depth limit is known due to the geometric growth of the number of nodes per level.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] DFS may also be used to collect a sample of graph nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] However, incomplete DFS, similarly to incomplete BFS, is biased towards nodes of high degree.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The edges traversed in this search form a Trémaux tree, a structure with important applications in graph theory.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes results in visiting the nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Iterative deepening is one technique to avoid this infinite loop and would reach all nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The result of a depth-first search of a graph can be conveniently described in terms of a spanning tree of the vertices reached during the search.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Based on this spanning tree, the edges of the original graph can be divided into three classes: **forward edges**, which point from a node of the tree to one of its descendants, **back edges**, which point from a node to one of its ancestors, and **cross edges**, which do neither.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Sometimes **tree edges**, edges which belong to the spanning tree itself, are classified separately from forward edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] If the original graph is undirected then all of its edges are tree edges or back edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] It is also possible to use depth-first search to linearly order the vertices of a graph or tree.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] For binary trees there is additionally **in-ordering** and **reverse in-ordering**.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] For example, when searching the directed graph below beginning at node A, the sequence of traversals is either A B D B A C A or A C D C A B A (choosing to first visit B or C from A is up to the algorithm).
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Note that repeat visits in the form of backtracking to a node, to check if it has still unvisited neighbors, are included here (even if it is found to have none).
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Thus the possible preorderings are A B D C and A C D B, while the possible postorderings are D B C A and D C B A, and the possible reverse postorderings are A C B D and A B C D.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Reverse postordering produces a topological sorting of any directed acyclic graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] This ordering is also useful in control-flow analysis as it often represents a natural linearization of the control flows.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The graph above might represent the flow of control in the code fragment below, and it is natural to consider this code in the order A B C D or A C B D but not natural to use the order A B D C or A C D B.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The recursive implementation will visit the nodes from the example graph in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The non-recursive implementation will visit the nodes as: A, E, F, B, D, C, G.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] 2. it delays checking whether a vertex has been discovered until the vertex is popped from the stack rather than making this check before adding the vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of the breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] Another possible implementation of iterative depth-first search uses a stack of iterators of the list of neighbors of a node, instead of a stack of nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] This yields the same traversal as recursive DFS.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] The computational complexity of DFS was investigated by John Reif.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] More precisely, given a graph G , let $O=(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be the ordering computed by the standard recursive DFS algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] This ordering is called the lexicographic depth-first search ordering.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] John Reif considered the complexity of computing the lexicographic depth-first search ordering, given a graph and a source.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] A decision version of the problem (testing whether some vertex u occurs before some vertex v in this order) is **P**-complete, meaning that it is "a nightmare for parallel processing".
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] A depth-first search ordering (not necessarily the lexicographic one), can be computed by a randomized parallel algorithm in the complexity class RNC.
[src:graph-algorithms/depth-first-search] As of 1997, it remained unknown whether a depth-first traversal could be constructed by a deterministic parallel algorithm, in the complexity class NC.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
