[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the actual shortest path (not just its distance) is desired, predecessor pointers can be stored in both searches.
