[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Theoretical research shows that an optimized bidirectional approach can be instance-optimal, meaning no correct algorithm can asymptotically relax fewer edges on the same graph instance.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Although Dijkstra's algorithm is optimal for graphs with non-negative edge weights, its practical runtime depends on both data structures and graph properties.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Using a binary heap results in a running time of O((V+E)logV).
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Alternatives such as Fibonacci heaps provide better theoretical bounds but often perform worse in real applications because of large constant factors.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph structure also plays a major role.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Sparse networks, such as road maps, allow Dijkstra's algorithm to operate efficiently since most vertices have low degree.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dense graphs increase relaxations and slow down the process.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of this, modern routing systems often use Dijkstra's algorithm together with preprocessing methods such as A* search, landmark heuristics, or contraction hierarchies, which significantly reduce the search space.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Memory locality is another important factor.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Cache-optimized priority queues and adjacency layouts can reduce latency for large graphs that exceed CPU cache limitations.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
