[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In optimization theory, **maximum flow problems** involve finding a feasible flow through a flow network that obtains the maximum possible flow rate.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem can be seen as a special case of more complex network flow problems, such as the circulation problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum value of an s-t flow (i.e., flow from source s to sink t) is equal to the minimum capacity of an s-t cut (i.e., cut severing s from t) in the network, as stated in the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem was first formulated in 1954 by T.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Ross as a simplified model of Soviet railway traffic flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Fulkerson created the first known algorithm, the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
