[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] where [11] refers to the 1955 secret report *Fundamentals of a Method for Evaluating Rail net Capacities* by Harris and Ross (see p.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The algorithms of Sherman and Kelner, Lee, Orecchia and Sidford, respectively, find an approximately optimal maximum flow but only work in undirected graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Orlin published a paper describing an $O(|V||E|)$ algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Liu, Richard Peng, Maximilian Probst Gutenberg, and Sushant Sachdeva published an almost-linear time algorithm running in $O(|E|^{1+o(1)})$ for the minimum-cost flow problem of which the maximum flow problem is a particular case.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] For the single-source shortest path (SSSP) problem with negative weights – another particular case of a minimum-cost flow problem – an algorithm running in almost-linear time has also been reported.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Both algorithms were deemed best papers at the 2022 Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Note that several maximum flows may exist, and if arbitrary real (or even arbitrary rational) values of flow are permitted (instead of just integers), there is either exactly one maximum flow, or infinitely many, since there are infinitely many linear combinations of the base maximum flows.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, if we send x units of flow on edge u in one maximum flow, and $y>x$ units of flow on u in another maximum flow, then for each $\Delta \in [0,y-x]$ we can send $x+\Delta$ units on u and route the flow on remaining edges accordingly, to obtain another maximum flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] If flow values can be any real or rational numbers, then there are infinitely many such $\Delta$ values for each pair $x,y$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The following tables show the historical development of algorithms for solving the maximum flow problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Many of the listed publications include similar tables comparing their results to earlier works.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] A strongly-polynomial time algorithm has polynomial time bounds that depend only on the number of inputs, but do not depend on the magnitude of these numbers.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the inputs are the vertices (numbered below as V ) and edges (numbered as E ).
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The complexity of each algorithm is stated using big O notation.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In parallel to the development of strongly-polynomial flow algorithms, there has been a long line of pseudo-polynomial and weakly polynomial time bounds, whose running time depends on the magnitude of the input capacities.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the value U refers to the largest edge capacity after rescaling all capacities to integer values.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] If each edge in a flow network has integral capacity, then there exists an integral maximal flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The claim is not only that the value of the flow is an integer, which follows directly from the max-flow min-cut theorem, but that the flow on *every edge* is integral.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] This is crucial for many combinatorial applications (see below), where the flow across an edge may encode whether the item corresponding to that edge is to be included in the set sought or not.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Given a network $N=(V,E)$ with a set of sources $S=\{s_{1},\ldots ,s_{n}\}$ and a set of sinks $T=\{t_{1},\ldots ,t_{m}\}$ instead of only one source and one sink, we are to find the maximum flow across N .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We can transform the multi-source multi-sink problem into a maximum flow problem by adding a *consolidated source* connecting to each vertex in S and a *consolidated sink*connected by each vertex in T (also known as *supersource* and *supersink*) with infinite capacity on each edge (See Fig.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Given a bipartite graph $G=(X\cup Y,E)$ , we are to find a maximum cardinality matching in G , that is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow in N is equal to the size of the maximum matching in G , and a maximum cardinality matching can be found by taking those edges that have flow 1 in an integral max-flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed acyclic graph $G=(V,E)$ , we are to find the minimum number of vertex-disjoint paths to cover each vertex in V .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Then it can be shown that $G'$ has a matching M of size m if and only if G has a vertex-disjoint path cover C containing m edges and $n-m$ paths, where n is the number of vertices in G .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, the problem can be solved by finding the maximum cardinality matching in $G'$ instead.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Assume we have found a matching M of $G'$ , and constructed the cover C from it.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Intuitively, if two vertices $u_{\mathrm {out} },v_{\mathrm {in} }$ are matched in M , then the edge $(u,v)$ is contained in C .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Similarly for each vertex $v_{\textrm {in}}$ in $G'$ – if it is matched, there is a single incoming edge into v in C ; otherwise v has no incoming edges in C .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Thus no vertex has two incoming or two outgoing edges in C , which means all paths in C are vertex-disjoint.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] To show that the cover C has size $n-m$ , we start with an empty cover and build it incrementally.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] To add a vertex u to the cover, we can either add it to an existing path, or create a new path of length zero starting at that vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The former case is applicable whenever either $(u,v)\in E$ and some path in the cover starts at v , or $(v,u)\in E$ and some path ends at v .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In the former case, the total number of edges in the cover is increased by 1 and the number of paths stays the same; in the latter case the number of paths is increased and the number of edges stays the same.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] It is now clear that after covering all n vertices, the sum of the number of paths and edges in the cover is n .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, if the number of edges in the cover is m , the number of paths is $n-m$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, the amount of flow passing through a vertex cannot exceed its capacity.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] To find the maximum flow across N , we can transform the problem into the maximum flow problem in the original sense by expanding N .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] First, each $v\in V$ is replaced by $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ , where $v_{\text{in}}$ is connected by edges going into v and $v_{\text{out}}$ is connected to edges coming out from v , then assign capacity $c(v)$ to the edge connecting $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ (see Fig.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In this expanded network, the vertex capacity constraint is removed and therefore the problem can be treated as the original maximum flow problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed graph $G=(V,E)$ and two vertices s and t , we are to find the maximum number of paths from s to t .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The paths must be independent, i.e., vertex-disjoint (except for s and t ).
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We can construct a network $N=(V,E)$ from G with vertex capacities, where the capacities of all vertices and all edges are 1 .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow is equal to the maximum number of independent paths from s to t .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In addition to the paths being edge-disjoint and/or vertex disjoint, the paths also have a length constraint: we count only paths whose length is exactly k , or at most k .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Most variants of this problem are NP-complete, except for small values of k .
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] A **closure** of a directed graph is a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The **closure problem** is the task of finding the maximum-weight or minimum-weight closure in a vertex-weighted directed graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In the baseball elimination problem there are *n* teams competing in a league.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] At a specific stage of the league season, *w**i* is the number of wins and *r**i* is the number of games left to play for team *i* and *r*ij is the number of games left against team *j*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] A team is eliminated if it has no chance to finish the season in the first place.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The task of the baseball elimination problem is to determine which teams are eliminated at each point during the season.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Schwartz proposed a method which reduces this problem to maximum network flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In this method a network is created to determine whether team *k* is eliminated.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* being the source and the sink respectively.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] One adds a game node*ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with *i* < *j* to *V*, and connects each of them from *s* by an edge with capacity *r**ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with two team nodes *i* and *j* to ensure one of them wins.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] One does not need to restrict the flow value on these edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Finally, edges are made from team node *i* to the sink node *t* and the capacity of *w**k* + *r**k* – *w**i* is set to prevent team *i* from winning more than *w**k* + *r**k*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In this method it is claimed team *k* is not eliminated if and only if a flow value of size *r*(*S* − {*k*}) exists in network *G*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned article it is proved that this flow value is the maximum flow value from *s* to *t*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In the airline industry a major problem is the scheduling of the flight crews.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The airline scheduling problem can be considered as an application of extended maximum network flow.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The input of this problem is a set of flights *F* which contains the information about where and when each flight departs and arrives.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In one version of airline scheduling the goal is to produce a feasible schedule with at most *k* crews.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] To solve this problem one uses a variation of the circulation problem called bounded circulation which is the generalization of network flow problems, with the added constraint of a lower bound on edge flows.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* as the source and the sink nodes.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] For the source and destination of every flight *i*, one adds two nodes to *V*, node *s**i* as the source and node *d**i* as the destination node of flight *i*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *t*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [1, 1] between each pair of *s**i* and *d**i*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *s**j*, if source *s**j* is reachable with a reasonable amount of time and cost from the destination of flight *i*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, ∞] between *s* and *t*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned method, it is claimed and proved that finding a flow value of *k* in *G* between *s* and *t* is equal to finding a feasible schedule for flight set *F* with at most *k* crews.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Another version of airline scheduling is finding the minimum needed crews to perform all the flights.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] To find an answer to this problem, a bipartite graph *G'* = (*A* ∪ *B*, *E*) is created where each flight has a copy in set *A* and set *B*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] If the same plane can perform flight *j* after flight *i*, *i*∈*A* is connected to *j*∈*B*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] A matching in G' induces a schedule for *F* and obviously maximum bipartite matching in this graph produces an airline schedule with minimum number of crews.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] As it is mentioned in the Application part of this article, the maximum cardinality bipartite matching is an application of maximum flow problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] There are some factories that produce goods and some villages where the goods have to be delivered.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] They are connected by a networks of roads with each road having a capacity c for maximum goods that can flow through it.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The problem is to find if there is a circulation that satisfies the demand.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] This problem can be transformed into a maximum-flow problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Add a sink node t and add edges from all villages vi to t with capacity di where di is the demand rate of village vi.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be this new network.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] If there exists a circulation, looking at the max-flow solution would give the answer as to how much goods have to be sent on a particular road for satisfying the demands.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] The problem can be extended by adding a lower bound on the flow on some edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] In their book, Kleinberg and Tardos present an algorithm for segmenting an image.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] They present an algorithm to find the background and the foreground in an image.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Indeed, for pixels in *A* (considered as the foreground), we gain *ai*; for all pixels in *B* (considered as the background), we gain *bi*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] On the border, between two adjacent pixels *i* and *j*, we loose *pij*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We now construct the network whose nodes are the pixel, plus a source and a sink, see Figure on the right.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the source to pixel *i* by an edge of weight *ai*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the pixel *i* to the sink by an edge of weight *bi*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] We connect pixel *i* to pixel *j* with weight *pij*.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] Now, it remains to compute a minimum cut in that network (or equivalently a maximum flow).
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] With negative constraints, the problem becomes strongly NP-hard even for simple networks.
[src:graph-algorithms/maximum-flow-problem] With positive constraints, the problem is polynomial if fractional flows are allowed, but may be strongly NP-hard when the flows must be integral.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum spanning tree** (**MST**) or **minimum weight spanning tree** is a subset of the edges of a connected, edge-weighted undirected graph that connects all the vertices together, without any cycles and with the minimum possible total edge weight.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] That is, it is a spanning tree whose sum of edge weights is as small as possible.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, any edge-weighted undirected graph (not necessarily connected) has a **minimum spanning forest**, which is a union of the minimum spanning trees for its connected components.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] There are many use cases for minimum spanning trees.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] One example is a telecommunications company trying to lay cable in a new neighborhood.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If it is constrained to bury the cable only along certain paths (e.g. roads), then there would be a graph containing the points (e.g. houses) connected by those paths.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Some of the paths might be more expensive, because they are longer, or require the cable to be buried deeper; these paths would be represented by edges with larger weights.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Currency is an acceptable unit for edge weight – there is no requirement for edge lengths to obey normal rules of geometry such as the triangle inequality.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A *spanning tree* for that graph would be a subset of those paths that has no cycles but still connects every house; there might be several spanning trees possible.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A *minimum spanning tree* would be one with the lowest total cost, representing the least expensive path for laying the cable.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If there are n vertices in the graph, then each spanning tree has *n* − 1 edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] There may be several minimum spanning trees of the same weight; in particular, if all the edge weights of a given graph are the same, then every spanning tree of that graph is minimum.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Since A and B differ despite containing the same nodes, there is at least one edge that belongs to one but not the other.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Among such edges, let *e*1 be the one with least weight; this choice is unique because the edge weights are all distinct.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Without loss of generality, assume *e*1 is in A.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] As B is an MST, {*e*1} ∪ *B* must contain a cycle C with *e*1.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] As a tree, A contains no cycles, therefore C must have an edge *e*2 that is not in A.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Since *e*1 was chosen as the unique lowest-weight edge among those belonging to exactly one of A and B, the weight of *e*2 must be greater than the weight of *e*1.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] As *e*1 and *e*2 are part of the cycle C, replacing *e*2 with *e*1 in B therefore yields a spanning tree with a smaller weight.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that B is an MST.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, if the edge weights are not all distinct then only the (multi-)set of weights in minimum spanning trees is certain to be unique; it is the same for all minimum spanning trees.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If the weights are *positive*, then a minimum spanning tree is, in fact, a minimum-cost subgraph connecting all vertices, since if a subgraph contains a cycle, removing any edge along that cycle will decrease its cost and preserve connectivity.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume the contrary, i.e. that e belongs to an MST *T*1.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Then deleting e will break *T*1 into two subtrees with the two ends of e in different subtrees.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The remainder of C reconnects the subtrees, hence there is an edge f of C with ends in different subtrees, i.e., it reconnects the subtrees into a tree *T*2 with weight less than that of *T*1, because the weight of f is less than the weight of e.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume that there is an MST T that does not contain e.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Adding e to T will produce a cycle, that crosses the cut once at e and crosses back at another edge e'.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Deleting e' we get a spanning tree *T*∖{*e'*} ∪ {*e*} of strictly smaller weight than T.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that T was a MST.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] By a similar argument, if more than one edge is of minimum weight across a cut, then each such edge is contained in some minimum spanning tree.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: if e was not included in the MST, removing any of the (larger cost) edges in the cycle formed after adding e to the MST, would yield a spanning tree of smaller weight.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If T is a tree of MST edges, then we can *contract* T into a single vertex while maintaining the invariant that the MST of the contracted graph plus T gives the MST for the graph before contraction.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] In all of the algorithms below, m is the number of edges in the graph and n is the number of vertices.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The first algorithm for finding a minimum spanning tree was developed by Czech scientist Otakar Borůvka in 1926 (see Borůvka's algorithm).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Its purpose was an efficient electrical coverage of Moravia.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm proceeds in a sequence of stages.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] In each stage, called *Boruvka step*, it identifies a forest F consisting of the minimum-weight edge incident to each vertex in the graph G, then forms the graph *G*1 = *G* \ *F* as the input to the next step.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Here *G* \ *F* denotes the graph derived from G by contracting edges in F (by the Cut property, these edges belong to the MST).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Since the number of vertices is reduced by at least half in each step, Boruvka's algorithm takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A second algorithm is Prim's algorithm, which was invented by Vojtěch Jarník in 1930 and rediscovered by Prim in 1957 and Dijkstra in 1959.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Basically, it grows the MST (T) one edge at a time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Initially, T contains an arbitrary vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] In each step, T is augmented with a least-weight edge (*x*,*y*) such that x is in T and y is not yet in T.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Cut property, all edges added to T are in the MST.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Its run-time is either *O*(*m* log *n*) or *O*(*m* + *n* log *n*), depending on the data-structures used.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A third algorithm commonly in use is Kruskal's algorithm, which also takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A fourth algorithm, not as commonly used, is the reverse-delete algorithm, which is the reverse of Kruskal's algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Its runtime is O(*m* log *n* (log log *n*)3).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] All four of these are greedy algorithms.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Since they run in polynomial time, the problem of finding such trees is in **FP**, and related decision problems such as determining whether a particular edge is in the MST or determining if the minimum total weight exceeds a certain value are in **P**.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Several researchers have tried to find more computationally-efficient algorithms.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] In a comparison model, in which the only allowed operations on edge weights are pairwise comparisons, Karger, Klein & Tarjan (1995) found a linear time randomized algorithm based on a combination of Borůvka's algorithm and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The fastest non-randomized comparison-based algorithm with known complexity, by Bernard Chazelle, is based on the soft heap, an approximate priority queue.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Its running time is *O*(*m* α(*m*,*n*)), where α is the classical functional inverse of the Ackermann function.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The function α grows extremely slowly, so that for all practical purposes it may be considered a constant no greater than 4; thus Chazelle's algorithm takes very close to linear time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] *m*/*n* ≥ log log log *n*), then a deterministic algorithm by Fredman and Tarjan finds the MST in time O(*m*).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm executes a number of phases.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Each phase executes Prim's algorithm many times, each for a limited number of steps.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The run-time of each phase is O(*m* + *n*).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If the number of vertices before a phase is n', the number of vertices remaining after a phase is at most ${\tfrac {n'}{2^{m/n'}}}$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Hence, at most log**n* phases are needed, which gives a linear run-time for dense graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] There are other algorithms that work in linear time on dense graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If the edge weights are integers represented in binary, then deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem in *O*(*m* + *n*) integer operations.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Whether the problem can be solved *deterministically* for a *general graph* in *linear time* by a comparison-based algorithm remains an open question.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem for planar graphs in linear time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Euler characteristic of planar graphs, *m* ≤ 3*n* - 6 ∈ *O*(*n*), so this is in time *O*(*n*).
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Given graph G where the nodes and edges are fixed but the weights are unknown, it is possible to construct a binary decision tree (DT) for calculating the MST for any permutation of weights.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Each internal node of the DT contains a comparison between two edges, e.g.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] "Is the weight of the edge between x and y larger than the weight of the edge between w and z?".
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The two children of the node correspond to the two possible answers "yes" or "no".
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] In each leaf of the DT, there is a list of edges from G that correspond to an MST.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime complexity of a DT is the largest number of queries required to find the MST, which is just the depth of the DT.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A DT for a graph G is called *optimal* if it has the smallest depth of all correct DTs for G.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] For every integer r, it is possible to find optimal decision trees for all graphs on r vertices by brute-force search.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Seth Pettie and Vijaya Ramachandran have found a provably optimal deterministic comparison-based minimum spanning tree algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The following is a simplified description of the algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Partition the graph to components with at most r vertices in each component.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] This partition uses a soft heap, which "corrupts" a small number of the edges of the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Use the optimal decision trees to find an MST for the uncorrupted subgraph within each component.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Add back the corrupted edges to the resulting forest to form a subgraph guaranteed to contain the minimum spanning tree, and smaller by a constant factor than the starting graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Apply the optimal algorithm recursively to this graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of all steps in the algorithm is *O*(*m*), *except for the step of using the decision trees*.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of this step is unknown, but it has been proved that it is optimal - no algorithm can do better than the optimal decision tree.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Thus, this algorithm has the peculiar property that it is *provably optimal* although its runtime complexity is *unknown*.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Research has also considered parallel algorithms for the minimum spanning tree problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] With a linear number of processors it is possible to solve the problem in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The problem can also be approached in a distributed manner.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If each node is considered a computer and no node knows anything except its own connected links, one can still calculate the distributed minimum spanning tree.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Frieze and Steele also proved convergence in probability.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Svante Janson proved a central limit theorem for weight of the MST.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] For uniform random weights in $[0,1]$ , the exact expected size of the minimum spanning tree has been computed for small complete graphs.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] There is a fractional variant of the MST, in which each edge is allowed to appear "fractionally".
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Formally, a **fractional spanning set** of a graph (V,E) is a nonnegative function *f* on *E* such that, for every non-trivial subset *W* of *V* (i.e., *W* is neither empty nor equal to *V*), the sum of *f*(*e*) over all edges connecting a node of *W* with a node of *V*\*W* is at least 1.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Intuitively, *f*(*e*) represents the fraction of e that is contained in the spanning set.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum fractional spanning set** is a fractional spanning set for which the sum $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ is as small as possible.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] If the fractions *f*(*e*) are forced to be in {0,1}, then the set *T* of edges with f(e)=1 are a spanning set, as every node or subset of nodes is connected to the rest of the graph by at least one edge of *T*.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Moreover, if *f* minimizes $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ , then the resulting spanning set is necessarily a tree, since if it contained a cycle, then an edge could be removed without affecting the spanning condition.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] The fractional MST problem can be solved in polynomial time using the ellipsoid method.
[src:graph-algorithms/minimum-spanning-tree] Minimum spanning trees have direct applications in the design of networks, including computer networks, telecommunications networks, transportation networks, water supply networks, and electrical grids (which they were first invented for, as mentioned above).
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] In the mathematical theory of directed graphs, a graph is said to be **strongly connected** if every vertex is reachable from every other vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The **strongly connected components** of a directed graph form a partition into subgraphs that are strongly connected themselves.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] It is possible to test the strong connectivity of a graph, or to find its strongly connected components, in linear time (that is, Θ(*V* + *E*)).
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] A directed graph is called **strongly connected** if there is a path in each direction between each pair of vertices of the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] That is, a path exists from the first vertex in the pair to the second, and another path exists from the second vertex to the first.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] In a directed graph *G* that may not itself be strongly connected, a pair of vertices *u* and *v* are said to be strongly connected to each other if there is a path in each direction between them.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The binary relation of being strongly connected is an equivalence relation, and the induced subgraphs of its equivalence classes are called **strongly connected components**.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Equivalently, a **strongly connected component** of a directed graph *G* is a subgraph that is strongly connected, and is maximal with this property: no set of additional edges or vertices from *G* can be included in the subgraph without breaking its property of being strongly connected.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The collection of strongly connected components forms a partition of the set of vertices of *G*.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] A strongly connected component *C* is called *trivial* when *C* consists of a single vertex which is not connected to itself with an edge, and *non-trivial* otherwise.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] If each strongly connected component is contracted to a single vertex, the resulting graph is a directed acyclic graph, the **condensation** of *G*.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has no strongly connected subgraphs with more than one vertex, because a directed cycle is strongly connected and every non-trivial strongly connected component contains at least one directed cycle.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Several algorithms based on depth-first search compute strongly connected components in linear time.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Although Kosaraju's algorithm is conceptually simple, Tarjan's and the path-based algorithm require only one depth-first search rather than two.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Previous linear-time algorithms are based on depth-first search which is generally considered hard to parallelize.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Fleischer et al. in 2000 proposed a divide-and-conquer approach based on reachability queries, and such algorithms are usually called reachability-based SCC algorithms.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The idea of this approach is to pick a random pivot vertex and apply forward and backward reachability queries from this vertex.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The two queries partition the vertex set into 4 subsets: vertices reached by both, either one, or none of the searches.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] One can show that a strongly connected component has to be contained in one of the subsets.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The vertex subset reached by both searches forms a strongly connected component, and the algorithm then recurses on the other 3 subsets.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The expected sequential running time of this algorithm is shown to be O(*n* log *n*), a factor of O(log *n*) more than the classic algorithms.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The parallelism comes from: (1) the reachability queries can be parallelized more easily (e.g. by a breadth-first search (BFS), and it can be fast if the diameter of the graph is small); and (2) the independence between the subtasks in the divide-and-conquer process.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] This algorithm performs well on real-world graphs, but does not have theoretical guarantee on the parallelism (consider if a graph has no edges, the algorithm requires O(*n*) levels of recursions).
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Blelloch et al. in 2016 shows that if the reachability queries are applied in a random order, the cost bound of O(*n* log *n*) still holds.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Furthermore, the queries then can be batched in a prefix-doubling manner (i.e.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] 1, 2, 4, 8 queries) and run simultaneously in one round.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] The overall span of this algorithm is log2 *n* reachability queries, which is probably the optimal parallelism that can be achieved using the reachability-based approach.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Maurer describes an algorithm for generating random strongly connected graphs, based on a modification of an algorithm for strong connectivity augmentation, the problem of adding as few edges as possible to make a graph strongly connected.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] When used in conjunction with the Gilbert or Erdős-Rényi models with node relabelling, the algorithm is capable of generating any strongly connected graph on *n* nodes, without restriction on the kinds of structures that can be generated.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] Strongly connected components are also used to compute the Dulmage–Mendelsohn decomposition, a classification of the edges of a bipartite graph, according to whether or not they can be part of a perfect matching in the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] According to Robbins' theorem, an undirected graph may be oriented in such a way that it becomes strongly connected, if and only if it is 2-edge-connected.
[src:graph-algorithms/strongly-connected-component] One way to prove this result is to find an ear decomposition of the underlying undirected graph and then orient each ear consistently.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] In computer science, a **topological sort** or **topological ordering** of a directed graph is a linear ordering of its vertices such that for every directed edge *(u,v)* from vertex *u* to vertex *v*, *u* comes before *v* in the ordering.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] For instance, the vertices of the graph may represent tasks to be performed, and the edges may represent constraints that one task must be performed before another; in this application, a topological ordering is just a valid sequence for the tasks.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Precisely, a topological sort is a graph traversal in which each node *v* is visited only after all its dependencies are visited*.* A topological ordering is possible if and only if the graph has no directed cycles, that is, if it is a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Any DAG has at least one topological ordering, and there are linear time algorithms for constructing it.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Topological sorting has many applications, especially in ranking problems such as feedback arc set.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Topological sorting is also possible when the DAG has disconnected components.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] The canonical application of topological sorting is in scheduling a sequence of jobs or tasks based on their dependencies.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] The jobs are represented by vertices, and there is an edge from *x* to *y* if job *x* must be completed before job *y* can be started (for example, when washing clothes, the washing machine must finish before we put the clothes in the dryer).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Then, a topological sort gives an order in which to perform the jobs.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] A closely related application of topological sorting algorithms was first studied in the early 1960s in the context of the PERT technique for scheduling in project management.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] In this application, the vertices of a graph represent the milestones of a project, and the edges represent tasks that must be performed between one milestone and another.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Topological sorting forms the basis of linear-time algorithms for finding the critical path of the project, a sequence of milestones and tasks that controls the length of the overall project schedule.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] It is also used to decide in which order to load tables with foreign keys in databases.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] One of these algorithms, first described by Kahn (1962), works by choosing vertices in the same order as the eventual topological sort.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] First, find a list of "start nodes" that have no incoming edges and insert them into a set S; at least one such node must exist in a non-empty (finite) acyclic graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] If the graph is a DAG, a solution will be contained in the list L (although the solution is not necessarily unique).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Otherwise, the graph must have at least one cycle and therefore a topological sort is impossible.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Reflecting the non-uniqueness of the resulting sort, the structure S can be simply a set or a queue or a stack.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Depending on the order that nodes n are removed from set S, a different solution is created.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] A variation of Kahn's algorithm that breaks ties lexicographically forms a key component of the Coffman–Graham algorithm for parallel scheduling and layered graph drawing.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] An alternative algorithm for topological sorting is based on depth-first search.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Each node *n* gets *prepended* to the output list L only after considering all other nodes that depend on *n* (all descendants of *n* in the graph).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Since each edge and node is visited once, the algorithm runs in linear time.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] This depth-first-search-based algorithm is the one described by Cormen et al.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] (2001); it seems to have been first described in print by Tarjan in 1976.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] On a parallel random-access machine, a topological ordering can be constructed in *O*((log *n*)2) time using a polynomial number of processors, putting the problem into the complexity class **NC2**.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] One method for doing this is to repeatedly square the adjacency matrix of the given graph, logarithmically many times, using min-plus matrix multiplication with maximization in place of minimization.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] The resulting matrix describes the longest path distances in the graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Sorting the vertices by the lengths of their longest incoming paths produces a topological ordering.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] An algorithm for parallel topological sorting on distributed memory machines parallelizes the algorithm of Kahn for a DAG $G=(V,E)$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] On a high level, the algorithm of Kahn repeatedly removes the vertices of indegree 0 and adds them to the topological sorting in the order in which they were removed.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Since the outgoing edges of the removed vertices are also removed, there will be a new set of vertices of indegree 0, where the procedure is repeated until no vertices are left.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] This algorithm performs $D+1$ iterations, where D is the longest path in G.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Each iteration can be parallelized, which is the idea of the following algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] In the following, it is assumed that the graph partition is stored on p processing elements (PE), which are labeled $0,\dots ,p-1$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Each PE i initializes a set of local vertices $Q_{i}^{1}$ with indegree 0, where the upper index represents the current iteration.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Since all vertices in the local sets $Q_{0}^{1},\dots ,Q_{p-1}^{1}$ have indegree 0, i.e., they are not adjacent, they can be given in an arbitrary order for a valid topological sorting.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] To assign a global index to each vertex, a prefix sum is calculated over the sizes of $Q_{0}^{1},\dots ,Q_{p-1}^{1}$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] So, each step, there are ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{p-1}|Q_{i}|}$ vertices added to the topological sorting.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] These vertices in $Q_{j}^{1}$ are removed, together with their corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] For each outgoing edge $(u,v)$ with endpoint v in another PE $l,j\neq l$ , the message $(u,v)$ is posted to PE l.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] After all vertices in $Q_{j}^{1}$ are removed, the posted messages are sent to their corresponding PE.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Each message $(u,v)$ received updates the indegree of the local vertex v.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] If the indegree drops to zero, v is added to $Q_{j}^{2}$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] This procedure repeats until there are no vertices left to process, hence ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{p-1}|Q_{i}^{D+1}|=0}$ .
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Below is a high level, single program, multiple data pseudo-code overview of this algorithm.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] The communication cost depends heavily on the given graph partition.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] As for runtime, on a CRCW-PRAM model that allows fetch-and-decrement in constant time, this algorithm runs in ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({\frac {m+n}{p}}+D(\Delta +\log n)\right)}$ , where D is again the longest path in G and Δ the maximum degree.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] The topological ordering can also be used to quickly compute shortest paths through a weighted directed acyclic graph.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Let V be the list of vertices in such a graph, in topological order.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] On a graph of n vertices and m edges, this algorithm takes Θ(*n* + *m*), i.e., linear, time.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] If a topological sort has the property that all pairs of consecutive vertices in the sorted order are connected by edges, then these edges form a directed Hamiltonian path in the DAG.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] If a Hamiltonian path exists, the topological sort order is unique; no other order respects the edges of the path.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Conversely, if a topological sort does not form a Hamiltonian path, the DAG will have two or more valid topological orderings, for in this case it is always possible to form a second valid ordering by swapping two consecutive vertices that are not connected by an edge to each other.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Therefore, it is possible to test in linear time whether a unique ordering exists, and whether a Hamiltonian path exists, despite the NP-hardness of the Hamiltonian path problem for more general directed graphs (i.e., cyclic directed graphs).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Topological orderings are also closely related to the concept of a linear extension of a partial order in mathematics.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] A partially ordered set is just a set of objects together with a definition of the "≤" inequality relation, satisfying the axioms of reflexivity (*x* ≤ *x*), antisymmetry (if *x* ≤ *y* and *y* ≤ *x* then *x* = *y*) and transitivity (if *x* ≤ *y* and *y* ≤ *z*, then *x* ≤ *z*).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] A total order is a partial order in which, for every two objects *x* and *y* in the set, either *x* ≤ *y* or *y* ≤ *x*.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Total orders are familiar in computer science as the comparison operators needed to perform comparison sorting algorithms.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] For finite sets, total orders may be identified with linear sequences of objects, where the "≤" relation is true whenever the first object precedes the second object in the order; a comparison sorting algorithm may be used to convert a total order into a sequence in this way.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] A linear extension of a partial order is a total order that is compatible with it, in the sense that, if *x* ≤ *y* in the partial order, then *x* ≤ *y* in the total order as well.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] One can define a partial ordering from any DAG by letting the set of objects be the vertices of the DAG, and defining *x* ≤ *y* to be true, for any two vertices *x* and *y*, whenever there exists a directed path from *x* to *y*; that is, whenever *y* is reachable from *x*.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] With these definitions, a topological ordering of the DAG is the same thing as a linear extension of this partial order.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Conversely, any partial ordering may be defined as the reachability relation in a DAG.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] One way of doing this is to define a DAG that has a vertex for every object in the partially ordered set, and an edge *xy* for every pair of objects for which *x* ≤ *y*.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] An alternative way of doing this is to use the transitive reduction of the partial ordering; in general, this produces DAGs with fewer edges, but the reachability relation in these DAGs is still the same partial order.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] By using these constructions, one can use topological ordering algorithms to find linear extensions of partial orders.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] By definition, the solution of a scheduling problem that includes a precedence graph is a valid solution to topological sort (irrespective of the number of machines), however, topological sort in itself is *not* enough to optimally solve a scheduling optimisation problem.
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Hu's algorithm is a popular method used to solve scheduling problems that require a precedence graph and involve processing times (where the goal is to minimise the largest completion time amongst all the jobs).
[src:graph-algorithms/topological-sorting] Like topological sort, Hu's algorithm is not unique and can be solved using DFS (by finding the largest path length and then assigning the jobs).
